entry.title: [sync] Migrate tests away from inexistent sync-stopped case
entry.content:
Function SyncServiceImplHarness::StopSyncServiceWithoutClearingData()

and other similar cases set up a state that is unreachable by users. In

the real product nowadays, sync cannot be temporarily stopped without

more specific semantics. Either sync is paused (e.g. persistent auth

error), permanently stopped (+ signout) or the device is offline. This

patch migrates tests to adhere to more realistic scenarios.



In some cases, the logic or the whole test becomes redundant and is

deleted. TwoClientPollingSyncTest is deleted altogether because the

test has been disabled for a long time, it isn't very realistic and

would require significant changes to avoid the dependency to the

now-removed StopSyncServiceWithoutClearingData() function.



In truth, there is one corner case that allows stopping sync, similar

to what tests did before this patch. This is the case on ChromeOS, if

the sync data is cleared from the dashboard. This is a very special

case and definitely not what the tests are aiming to test.

entry.title: Initialize Perfetto system tracing backend on Android
entry.content:
The Perfetto system tracing backend was disabled on Android because

of binary size concerns. The specific problem was that it included

consumer IPC messages that were never used on Android, but were linked

with the binary nevertheless.



Recently the system backend was split into producer and consumer side,

and after aosp/2446369 it became possible to initialize them

separately. Now the consumer IPC won't be linked with the final binary

if it's not used in the code.



This change enables the system tracing backend on Android. It won't

have any effect in the non-SDK build, and will make it possible to

connect to the system tracing service in the SDK build.

entry.title: web-engine: Add origin allow list
entry.content:
We want to be able to allow developers to limit

WebEngine to particular domains if they are concerned

about their application interacting with other websites.



Had to make the allowlist expect an ArrayList because the

Bundle we used to transport parameters only supports sending

arraylists. The alternative was adding an API like `addAllowListOrigin`

and hiding those details but it would be confusing to developers

that the allowlist only starts applying once you provide

a host while "setAllowList" seems a lot more clear.



We are using strings instead of android.net.Uri because we are

only interested in the origin and don't want to give a confusing

public facing API.



This uses NavigationThrottles so the good thing is it will

still call all the regular navigation observer methods like

navigation failure when the domain is blocked.

entry.title: Revert "[balance-text] Replace `WhiteSpace()` in `IsTabHTMLSpanElement`"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a689d7b6339bcc78fad9709380e4d45de4945e80.



Reason for revert: crbug.com/1431935



`IsTabHTMLSpanElement` tries to detect spans created by

`CreateTabSpanElement`, which sets `white-space:pre`[1].



The CL changed it to include `pre-wrap` as well, which caused

a regression in crbug.com/1431935.



Adding `&& !style.ShouldWrapLine()` can also fix, but this

code is really about detecting an artificial span

`CreateTabSpanElement` created, so making it semantics doesn't

have much meanings. Simple revert should be fine and safe.



At the point of the CL, the `WhiteSpace()` function was likely

to be slower, but further development made it not slow, so

using `WhiteSpace()` is ok, as long as it doesn't have to

worry about when `text-wrap` is set to new values.



Also note that the original logic can misdetect spans created

by authors or JS. crbug.com/1431935#c5 indicates editing JS

libraries have implemented browser-specific behaviors that

keeping the original behavior looks more important than making

the detection more correct.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/core/editing/editing_utilities.cc;l=1149?q=CreateTabSpanElement&ss=chromium





Original change's description:

> [balance-text] Replace `WhiteSpace()` in `IsTabHTMLSpanElement`

>

> This patch replaces `WhiteSpace() == Pre` in

> `IsTabHTMLSpanElement` with more semantical function

> `IsCollapsibleWhiteSpace` to prepare for refactoring the

> `white-space` property to a shorthand.

>

> This code was added in crrev.com/c/697044 to check if a TAB

> character is preserved. As part of the efforts to change the

> `white-space` property to a shorthand, this change eliminates

> the direct access to the `WhiteSpace()` property.

>

> This change will apply the fix in crrev.com/c/697044 not only

> to `pre` but also to `pre-wrap` and `break-spaces` where TAB

> characters are also preserved.

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2/h265: Fix up DPB and decode param setting
entry.content:
Rewrite the existing H.264 DPB entry and decode parameter control

setting code to match HEVC.



The changes are quite extensive. For H.264, the control values were

filled into the control data structures in SubmitFrameMetadata(), but

only passed to the kernel in SubmitDecode(). The data structure had to

be kept around as private data.



This is totally unnecessary and would actually work against slice-based

decoding. The control data only depends on frame headers and the first

slice header, both of which are available and have been parsed when

SubmitFrameMetadata() is called, so it can be passed to the kernel as

soon as it's filled in. Since it's tied to a certain request FD, the

kernel's request API framework keeps the control around and associates

it with the raw data once it's passed in.



For HEVC we construct and submit the decode parameter control in

SubmitFrameMetadata(). This gets rid of the private data, but requires

adding the ref_pic_set_* (ReferencePictureSet) parameters to the

function across all the HEVC decoders and unit tests. This alone

accounts for half of the diff. The rest is the same as before, filling

in the control data structure fields from our parsed data.

result hash against Gstreamer

entry.title: [Device Tier] Adding changes for geting device PPI.
entry.content:
For segmenting the devices into tiers and users into various

producutivity groups, device PPIis required as an input to the model.

There is no API in chrome,that could be directly used to serve the

purpose.Hence adding new method as utility in SegmentationPlatform.



How to calculate Device PPI?

Math.max(display.getXdpi(), display.getYdpi())

If Xdpi == Ydpi, these two formulas will yield the same results.



Looking at the data from crash dashboard, Xdpi and Ydpi are pretty

close. So the difference would be minimum.



In this CL, using ContextUtils.getApplicationContext().getResources().getDisplayMetrics()

as display. This would give the device internal/external display on

whatever chrome is running.
